s multiple commits, run the CLI subprocess against that repo, and assert each reported category count equals the expected counts derived from the scripted history.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.03,"Integration":0.12,"System":0.83,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"The output is identical whether the changes being analyzed are staged or unstaged.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"REAL-INFRA and MOCK-HIDE: staged vs unstaged correctness depends on actual git index/worktree semantics, which are OS/filesystem + subprocess behaviors. In-process mocks can easily hide discrepancies in how CLI chooses diff targets. REJECTION-GATE: I considered Integration, but behavior text explicitly compares \"staged or unstaged,\" a real git state boundary that needs real repo/index interaction. Higher levels are disqualified because there is no AI/ML dependency or multi-step agent pipeline.","test_description":"Prepare equivalent changes in two real temp repos (or two runs in one repo): one staged, one unstaged. Run the CLI subprocess in each state and assert structured stdout outputs are byte-for-byte identical (or semantically identical after stable normalization).","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.04,"Integration":0.15,"System":0.79,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}}]}
